SIMPLE: literator
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Literator
<hw>Lit"er*a`tor</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"⟦etil⟧r*⟦amac⟧`t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>litterator</ets>, <ets>literator</ets>. See
<er>Letter</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who teaches the letters or
elements of knowledge; a petty schoolmaster.</def>
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person devoted to the study of literary trifles,
esp. trifles belonging to the literature of a former age.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That class of subjects which are interesting to the regular
<qex>literator</qex> or black-letter ⟦ldquo⟧ bibliomane,⟦rdquo⟧ simply
because they have once been interesting.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A learned person; a literatus.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Literature</ent>⟦br⟧
